Your ONLY job is to confirm each fold actually closes its hole against the live code. Do NOT
re-review §2.6, §2.7, terminal-edge synthesis, the plumbing table, or any other already-
confirmed section — those were CONFIRMED sound in pass 4. Focus only on the two items below.
End with a single verdict line.

## The spec to review

`docs/superpowers/specs/2026-07-12-vocab01-goal-actions-redesign.md` (read §2.2 and §2.8 in
full, plus §3 table rows for `_infer_capability_tags`, `_unwrap_mcp_json`/`_select_chain`,
and the planner call; plus §5 tests (h)(k)(l)(m) and §6).

## Code to ground against

- This repo: `core/planner/search.py` (matching + terminal predicate), and the live
  `registry.db` for actual `intent_tags` (the `capability` table).
- Sibling repo `~/.hermes/hermes-adapter`: `hermes_adapter/tools/cli_registry.py`
  (`_infer_capability_tags` ~501-568, `_unwrap_mcp_json` ~573, `_select_chain` ~668,
  the `plan_cli_chain` call site ~899-905).

## Fold 1 — §2.2 max-one-verb-per-live-terminal (was: false disjoint-map-values claim)

The 4th pass proved `send_mail` (live `intent_tags='notify,send'`) matches BOTH `email:{send}`
AND `notify:{notify}` even though the map values are disjoint. The fold:
- Replaced the invariant with **max-one-verb-per-LIVE-terminal** (a runtime assertion over
  actual tags, not map-value disjointness).
- Added a disambiguation rule: when a terminal matches >1 verb, the verb keyed on the rarer
  tag wins (so `send_mail` → `email`, since `send` is rarer than the shared `notify`).
- Test (h) is now RED-first, reproducing the double-match; test (k) asserts a `notify` goal
  does NOT route to send_mail.

CONFIRM: (a) Is the new invariant actually correct and does it CATCH the send_mail
double-match (vs. the old map-only check that missed it)? (b) Is the specificity/rarer-tag
disambiguation rule well-defined and deterministic — any tie or edge case where it fails to
pick a single verb? (c) Does the rule correctly resolve `send_mail`→`email` given the LIVE
tag distribution (how many live terminals carry `send` vs `notify`)? Verify against
registry.db. (d) Any NEW hole the fold introduces?

## Fold 2 — §2.8 explicit decode + reinference (was: false "reuse existing loop" claim)

The 4th pass proved the "reuse `_infer_capability_tags`'s vocab-reject loop" claim false: that
loop runs pre-planner (line 826, before the ~899 planner call), handles only port tags, and
`_select_chain` swallows any structured planner error into a generic "no healthy chain"
(686/706). The fold:
- Adds an explicit decode: `_unwrap_mcp_json`/`_select_chain` must detect the structured
  `{"error": "unknown action verb: <v>; known:[...]"}` payload BEFORE flattening and raise a
  typed `UnknownActionVerbError(verb, known)`.
- Adds a NEW one-shot reinference at the planner call site catching that error, re-inferring
  with the rejected verb + known list named, re-calling `plan_cli_chain` once, then raising.
- Tests (l)(m) cover the decode and the single reinference.

CONFIRM: (a) Does the decode point (`_unwrap_mcp_json` vs the call site) actually sit BEFORE
the generic-error raise, so the structured payload is still intact when decoded? (b) Is the
one-shot reinference correctly bounded (exactly one, then raise — no loop)? (c) Does the
registry side actually EMIT the structured `{"error": ...}` in the shape the adapter decodes
(check the ops error channel / where plan_cli_chain would return it)? (d) Any NEW hole?

## Output format (REQUIRED)

Prose findings on ONLY these two folds, then end with EXACTLY ONE final line:

`PLAN-READY`

or

`NOT-PLAN-READY`

If NOT-PLAN-READY, precede it with a numbered list naming the specific remaining hole in one
of the two folds, with the concrete code/data fact that contradicts the fold.
